article.headline: Virginia Tech 84, Hofstra 59
article.story: EDS: Virginia Tech 84, Hofstra 59; UPDATES with championship game opponent. AP Photo NYFF102 By JIM O'CONNELL AP Basketball Writer NEW YORK (AP) -- Virginia Tech did just what it was supposed to against a team missing its key player -- win big. Freshman Jeff Allen had 17 points and nine rebounds and the Hokies beat Hofstra 84-59 on Friday night in the opening round of the Aeropostale Holiday Festival. The Pride were without senior guard Antoine Agudio, the second-leading scorer in the nation with a 26.8 average. Agudio sprained his left ankle in practice on Wednesday. "That's a pretty big difference without Agudio," Virginia Tech coach Seth Greenberg said. "Their young kids play off him and they didn't have anyone to play off." The Hokies took advantage of Agudio's absence right away, opening the game with a 14-2 run. They closed the half with an 11-2 spurt to take a 45-23 lead. The Hokies enjoyed their size advantage inside, especially the 6-foot-7, 258-pound Allen, who made all four of his shots in the first half. He finished 6-for-8 from the field and just missed his sixth double-double of the season. "He's enormous. He has great hands and lift and knows how to use his body," Greenberg said of Allen. "We did a nice job of getting Jeff established. We made the extra pass and defended when we had to defend." The Hokies, who shot 56 percent for the game, will play St. John's, which beat Marist 62-59, for the title on Saturday at Madison Square Garden. Deron Washington and A.D. Vassallo both added 17 points for the Hokies (7-5), who had lost two out of three including their Atlantic Coast Conference opener to Wake Forest. "It was really positive coming off a tough loss to see us play with such energy," Greenberg said. Freshman Charles Jenkins had 13 points for the defending champion Pride (2-7). Despite receiving treatment all day Thursday and right up until warmups on Friday, Agudio missed his first game after starting the first 103 of his career. "Without Agudio we are a far different team. We struggle to score points," Hofstra coach Tom Pecora said. "They could have beat us by 40 or 50 if they kept the press on and put the wood to us." Pecora said Agudio will be day-to-day. "Initially the doctors and trainer said two to four weeks," Pecora said. "They taped it up today and he jogged in the hallway. They were amazed at what he had done in 48 hours." Agudio said it was "hard to sit on the sideline. "I have to hope that the younger players get some confidence from this," he said. Hofstra just couldn't replace Agudio's shooting and floor leadership. He came into the game shooting 47.8 percent from 3-point range and he was held to less than 22 points just once the entire season. The Pride shot 34 percent for the game, including 1-for-10 from 3-point range. "You look at that number and you see what he means to us," Pecora said. "I'm getting tired of saying they're still freshmen but every time I check they still are." Virginia Tech, which is 10-2 all-time at Madison Square Garden, led by as many as 33 points. Hofstra beat St. John's in last year's championship game, the Pride's third title. They also won in 1998 and 1999. They are 7-2 all-time in the Festival and 9-3 in their last 12 games at Madison Square Garden. This was the first meeting between the schools.
